	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Regulatory reform critical to future of the Kenyan sugar sector </h1>

			
			<h4>
												18 November 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Competition for sugar cane among millers in Western Kenya has broken out into violence, with sugar cane trailers ‘hijacked’ as millers seek to assert their contractual rights to cane supplies. The additional security requirements are increasing production costs. Mumias, for example, has reported ‘a 27 per cent increase in administrative costs and 46 per cent in operating expenses’ at the same time as a 27% drop in production and a marginal decline in revenues. </p><p>The ‘cane war’ is seen as threatening the long-term future of the Kenyan sugar sector, in view of the scheduled removal of the COMESA safeguard arrangement in 2014. According to press reports, currently ‘local cane production is twice as expensive compared to Malawi, Tanzania and Uganda’, while ‘factories are operating at less than 70% capacity.’ </p><p>The ‘cane wars’ have led to criticism of the Kenya Sugar Board (KSB) for its failure to maintain ‘order and balance’ in the sugar sector. In August 2012, the Sugar Arbitration Tribunal added its voice, maintaining that KSB was ‘issuing operating licences to new sugar factories without following due process’ under the 2001 Sugar Act. The Act requires new millers to have the necessary capacity – infrastructure, personnel and raw materials – in place to operate efficiently prior to the issuing of the licences. It also prohibits the establishment of competing mills within 40 km of each other. The Tribunal accused KSB of contravening both of these provisions ‘by licensing new millers without regarding the fact that cane development was not at par with the number of factories being licensed’. This, it maintained, was ‘the foundation of the cases of cane poaching being witnessed’. </p><p>The KSB Chair, in response, maintained that the current formula ‘restricts farmers to a specific miller’, creating ‘empires within the sugar belts where millers hive off territories and claim ownership and control of everything within’. This, it was argued, was ‘detrimental to cane development because some companies mismanage the crop that falls under their zones’. The KSB chairperson rejected claims that KSB ‘had licensed new operators who had not met regulatory criteria’, maintaining that ‘the regulator was confident that the investments by new operators in these regions were well placed’. </p><p>It is against this background that the Kenyan Parliament is debating the Sugar Act Amendment Bill. The Act proposes ‘the setting up of a trustee to act as an industry regulator’ and assist in ‘developing policies to promote the interests of various stakeholders’. KSB opposes this reform, believing that it undermines its mandate. </p><p>It was reported in the Ugandan press also in September that increased sales of Ugandan sugar on the Kenyan market have led to changes in bond requirements for sugar being imported into Uganda via Mombasa under reduced tariff arrangements. These shipments of sugar to Uganda now require a cash bond to be lodged equivalent to the duty that would be charged should the sugar be sold on the Kenyan market. This measure was introduced in response to concerns that Kenyan imports of Ugandan sugar were actually cargoes of sugar from overseas, destined for Uganda, but which were being diverted onto the Kenyan market. </p><p>The Ugandan Revenue Authority has denied these allegations and invited inspection of sugar factories to verify the origin of Ugandan sugar exported to Kenya. The action of the Kenyan Revenue Authority is perceived to be in contravention of existing EAC commitments and mechanisms. Sugar prices in Uganda have increased by between 13 and 25% as a result of the shortages generated by the delays in delivery of sugar through Mombasa. </p><p>In neighbouring Tanzania, sugar production for 2011/12 at the Tanzanian subsidiary operation of Alteo, the new merged Mauritian sugar company, is reported to have increased by 5.8%, contributing additional earnings to the Mauritian group’s profits.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Business Daily</i>, ‘Millers’ wars hit plans to meet Comesa sugar safeguards deadline’, 17 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.trademarksa.org/news/millers-wars-hit-plans-meet-comesa-sugar-safeguards-deadline" target="_self">http://www.trademarksa.org/news/millers-wars-hit-plans-meet-comesa-sugar...</a></p><p><i>New Vision</i> (Uganda), ‘Kenya blocks Uganda goods over new tax’, 18 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.trademarksa.org/news/kenya-blocks-uganda-goods-over-new-tax" target="_self">http://www.trademarksa.org/news/kenya-blocks-uganda-goods-over-new-tax</a></p><p>&nbsp;<i>East African Business Weekly</i>, ‘Sugar prices rise again’, 17 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201209180383.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201209180383.html</a></p><p>Reuters, ‘Mauritian sugar firm DRBC's profit up 19 pct before merger’, 14 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://af.reuters.com/article/mauritiusNews/idAFL5E8KE14R20120914" target="_self">http://af.reuters.com/article/mauritiusNews/idAFL5E8KE14R20120914</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The outbreak of violence in Western Kenya highlights the weakness of the current sugar sector regulatory framework, including as regards the enforcement of contracts between cane growers and millers. A critical question is whether this requires a strengthening and reform of the Kenya Sugar Board or a new institutional framework for the regulation of the sugar sector.</p><p>A comparison of regional experiences could well be relevant in this respect, as well as in respect of regional best practices for self-regulation of the sugar sector.</p><p>The current developments in Kenya reflect the widely differing conditions of payment and service provision between milling companies and the absence of effective enforcement of contractual obligations. While some millers may have been late in responding to the situation of more competition emerging in the sugar milling sector, it should come as no surprise in a context of rising input costs and food prices and the absence of an effective framework for the enforcement of contractual commitments that farmers are shopping around for the best price for their cane, and then ignoring their repayment obligations.</p><p>Stronger farmers’ organisations to both counter the power of sugar millers and bring order into farmers’ dealings with the mills (including in respecting contractual commitments) would therefore appear to be necessary.</p><p>In addition to regional practices, it is particularly important for the Kenyan sugar sector to get to grips with the underlying cost-competitiveness issues if it is to survive free competition from other COMESA sugar producers beyond 2014. Strengthened intra-industry dialogue would provide a framework for this. This will involve not just reducing costs, but also opening up new revenue streams and establishing a more satisfactory framework for the distribution of the benefits of such investments among millers and farmers.</p>
		</div>
		
